def createData(alpha, beta, nu, n = 1000):
    ## n: number of data points
    ## alpha: amplitude (importance)
    ## beta: frequency (complexity)
    ## nu: noise
    np.random.seed(371)
    x1 = np.random.normal(size=n)
    x2 = np.random.normal(size=n)
    X = np.column_stack((x1, x2))  # design matrix

    ## Now compute color
    y = x2 > (alpha * np.sin(beta * x1) + nu * np.random.normal(size=n))
    ## this is how the data looks like
    return X, y

def plot_dataset(X, y, alpha, beta, nu):
    ax = plt.axes()
    ax.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c=y, s=20, edgecolors='k')
    ax.set_aspect("equal")
    ax.set_title(f"alpha = {alpha}, beta = {beta}, nu = {nu}")
    plt.show()

1.1.2¶

n_estimators defines how many decision trees are made in the random forest. Larger number of trees tends to improve the model's performance as it reduces the risk of overfitting. But using more trees will increase the training time, since the model has to train more individual trees.

## DBplot from textbook
def DBPlot(m, X, y, nGrid = 100):
    ## find the extent of the features
    ## and add 'padding', here "1" to it.  Adjust as needed!
    x1_min, x1_max = X[:, 0].min() - 1, X[:, 0].max() + 1
            # note: indexing assumes X is a np.array!
    x2_min, x2_max = X[:, 1].min() - 1, X[:, 1].max() + 1
    ## make a dense grid (nGrid x nGrid) in this extent
    xx1, xx2 = np.meshgrid(np.linspace(x1_min, x1_max, nGrid),
                           np.linspace(x2_min, x2_max, nGrid))
    ## Convert two grids into two columns
    XX = np.column_stack((xx1.ravel(), xx2.ravel()))
    ## predict on the grid
    hatyy = m.predict(XX).reshape(xx1.shape)
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,8))
    ## show the predictions as an semi-transparent image
    _ = plt.imshow(hatyy, extent=(x1_min, x1_max, x2_min, x2_max),
                   aspect="auto",
                   interpolation='none', origin='lower',
                   alpha=0.3)
    ## add the actual data points on the image
    plt.scatter(X[:,0], X[:,1], c=y, s=30, edgecolors='k')
    plt.xlim(x1_min, x1_max)
    plt.ylim(x2_min, x2_max)
    plt.show()
In [39]:
def experiment(X, y, n_value):
    # (a)
    Xt, Xv, yt, yv = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=371)

    best_acc = 0
    best_n = None
    best_model = None

    # (b)
    for n in n_value:
        clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=n, random_state=371)
        clf.fit(Xt, yt)
        y_pred = clf.predict(Xv)
        acc = accuracy_score(yv, y_pred)
        print(f"n = {n}, accuracy = {acc}")
        if acc > best_acc:
            best_acc = acc
            best_n = n
            best_model = clf

    # (c)
    print(f"Best n = {best_n}, accuracy = {best_acc}")

    # (d)
    DBPlot(best_model, Xv, yv)

1.1.4¶

  • For simple data with low noise, the number of estimator is 10 which is pretty low. Model can reach good accuracy quickly.
  • For simple data with more noise, the number of estimator is 200 which is more than the one with no noise. Noise increase the number of estimator needed.
  • For complex data with low noise, the number of estimator is 400 which is much more than simple data with low noise.
  • For complex data with more noise, the number of estimator is 600 which is much more than complex data with low noise.

Summary: more complex data need more number of estimators. Higher noise need more number of estimators as well and it reduces the accuracy.

In [53]:
n_value = [1, 100, 200, 300, 400, 500, 600, 700, 800, 900, 1000]

train_acc_list = []
val_acc_list = []

def experiment(X, y, n_values):
    Xt, Xv, yt, yv = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=371)

    best_acc = 0
    best_n = None
    best_model = None

    for n in n_values:
        clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=n, random_state=42)
        clf.fit(Xt, yt)

        y_train_pred = clf.predict(Xt)
        y_val_pred = clf.predict(Xv )

        train_acc = accuracy_score(yt, y_train_pred)
        val_acc = accuracy_score(yv, y_val_pred)

        train_acc_list.append(train_acc)
        val_acc_list.append(val_acc)

        print(f"n = {n}, train acc = {train_acc}, val acc = {val_acc}")

        if val_acc > best_acc:
            best_acc = val_acc
            best_n = n
            best_model = clf
            
    print(f"Best n = {best_n}, val acc = {best_acc}")

Left part 2x2, right part 3x2. Can't perform this multiplication.

  • c (2x3)

$$ = \begin{bmatrix} 0 * 1 + 6 * 0 & 0 * 0 + 6 * -1 & 0 * 0 + 6 * 1\\ 5 * 1 + 3 * 0 & 5 * 0 + 3 * -1 & 5 * 0 + 3 * 1 \\ \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 0 & -6 & 6\\ 5 & -3 & 3\\ \end{bmatrix} $$

def matrix_product(A, B):
    # Dim check
    m, n = A.shape
    n2, b = B.shape

    if n != n2:
        return "Matrix dimension not match"
    else:
        result = np.zeros((m, b))

        for i in range(m):
            for j in range(b):
                for k in range(n):
                    result[i, j] += A[i, k] * B[k, j]
        
        return result.astype(int)

def plot(X, groups, title=""):
    ax = plt.axes()
    ax.set_aspect("equal")
    unique_groups = np.unique(groups)

    for group in unique_groups:
        indices = (groups == group)
        segment = X[indices]
        ax.plot(segment[:, 0], segment[:, 1], marker='o', label=group)

    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

In [84]:
def Rot(alpha_degrees):
    alpha = np.pi * alpha_degrees / 180  
    return np.array([
        [np.cos(alpha), -np.sin(alpha)],
        [np.sin(alpha),  np.cos(alpha)]
    ])
